Structure Excavated at Xultún
                    
 					http://www.history.com/news/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/xultun_001.jpg
                    
					In 2010, a room featuring murals was discovered at the Maya archaeological site of Xultún, located in Guatemala’s Petén rainforest. Researchers believe it served as the studio of a scribe or calendar priest some 1,200 years ago. (Credit: Tyrone Turner/National Geographic)
